The Inflation You Live Isn‚Äôt the Inflation They Measure
Inflation is supposed to be simple. Prices go up. Your money buys less. The Consumer Price Index tells you by how much.
But the inflation people actually experience is often not a higher sticker price. It is the same sticker price for a worse product.
And that is exactly where the CPI is weakest.
The Bureau of Labor Statistics will tell you it adjusts for ‚Äúquality‚Äù so the index reflects what you are really getting. If a product improves, the CPI should not treat the full sticker price increase as inflation. If the product gets worse, the CPI should do the opposite.
In theory, that sounds symmetrical.
In practice, it is not.
Quality improvements tend to be measurable in categories where the government has built sophisticated models. Electronics get faster. Screens get sharper. Storage increases. Vehicle features expand. These improvements can be quantified, regression-modeled, and translated into effective price declines even when the sticker price stays flat.
Quality degradation is different. It is real, but it is harder to model. It shows up in durability, service, reliability, materials, access, and time. These are not neat parameters. They are lived experience. And when something is hard to measure, it gets missed.
Start with durability. If a washing machine lasts eight years instead of twenty, the sticker price can be unchanged and the cost of ownership still rises sharply. You are paying more per year of useful service. That is inflation in everything but name.
Or consider the shift from ownership to subscription. Software that once cost a few hundred dollars and worked for years now charges monthly in perpetuity. The subscription may come with updates, but the total cost over time rises. The consumer pays more to keep using what they already had.
Service quality has degraded across the economy in ways that are obvious to anyone who has tried to solve a problem lately. It is harder to reach a human being. Customer service is routed through automation designed to absorb complaints rather than resolve them. Retail stores operate with fewer staff and longer waits. Returns take longer. Assistance is discouraged. The cost is not only money. It is time and friction.
That time is not free. It is part of what you are paying.
Uber is a clean example. The original product was not simply ‚Äúa ride.‚Äù It was a bundle: predictable pickup, higher standards than taxis, lower friction, and an all-in price where tipping was not expected. Over time, that bundle degraded. Reliability declined. Standards slipped. Tipping returned as a quasi-required surcharge because the base pay no longer supported the original service level. The nominal fare does not always reflect the change, but the effective price of the original service is higher.
Air travel is another. The fare might not rise in proportion to the deterioration in the experience because legroom shrinks, baggage fees appear, meals disappear, and service is stripped down to the minimum. Fees that were once bundled become separate charges. The customer pays more for less, but the pricing architecture makes it harder to capture.
Then there is material substitution. Metal becomes plastic. Components become thinner. Packaging becomes cheaper. Products become harder to repair. The sticker price holds. The product is worse. The consumer bears the cost through earlier replacement and lower performance.
The CPI is not blind to every one of these dynamics, but it is structurally better at capturing measurable upgrades than it is at capturing widespread degradation. That creates a bias.
And the bias runs in one direction.
This does not require a conspiracy theory. It is a measurement reality and an institutional reality.
The Boskin Commission in the 1990s argued CPI overstated inflation and recommended changes that lowered it. Lower measured inflation reduces Social Security obligations, reduces payments on inflation-indexed bonds, slows tax bracket adjustments, and flatters real GDP. Those are political incentives. Again, no secret plot is required. The direction of the ‚Äúerror correction‚Äù is simply convenient.
The exact magnitude of CPI‚Äôs understatement can be debated. But the direction should not be.
When the index credits quality improvements that are easy to quantify while missing degradation that is hard to model, it will understate inflation relative to what households experience. And because so much of modern consumer life now consists of degraded service, reduced durability, unbundled fees, and friction shifted onto the user, the understatement is not trivial.
The consequences are not academic. CPI is not just a statistic. It is a lever. When it is lower, retirees receive smaller cost-of-living adjustments. Workers negotiating wages anchor to a number that understates their lived reality. Real growth is overstated. The transfer runs from savers and wage earners to debtors and the state.
Inflation does not only happen when prices rise. It also happens when products and services deteriorate while the sticker price stays the same.
That is inflation you cannot ignore. And it is inflation the CPI systematically struggles to see.
